3":"1251年–1313年","about 1261":"大约1261年","1238":"1238年","1259":"1259年","1314":"1314年","1313":"1313年","1264":"1264年","before 1285":"1285年之前","1285":"1285年","after 11 August 1313":"1313年8月11日之后","1251":"1251年","about 1251":"大约1251年","1290":"1290年","North Reston, Lincolnshire, England":"英国林可爾史爾諾斯 雷斯頓","Petsoe Manor, Buckinghamshire, England":"英国巴金哈姆爾左 曼諾","Bedfordshire, England":"英国貝德福爾","lifeSummary":"Mrs Joan Chamberlain于大约1251年出生在英国林可爾史爾諾斯 雷斯頓。她于大约1261年与Sir William Chamberlain Knight在英国林可爾史爾諾斯 雷斯頓结婚。他们至少是1个儿子的父母。她去世于1313年8月11日之后在她的家乡。"},"hr":{"about 1251–after 11 August 1313":"oko 1251.–nakon 11. kolovoza 1313.","1238–1285":"1238–1285","1264–1314":"1264.–1314","1251–1313":"1251–1313","about 1261":"oko 1261.","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1314":"1314","1313":"1313","1264":"1264.","before 1285":"prije 1285.","1285":"1285","after 11 August 1313":"nakon 11. kolovoza 1313.","1251":"1251","about 1251":"oko 1251.","1290":"1290","North Reston, Lincolnshire, England":"North Reston, Lincolnshire, England","Petsoe Manor, Buckinghamshire, England":"Petsoe Manor, Buckinghamshire, England","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England"},"cs":{"about 1251–after 11 August 1313":"okolo 1251–po 11. srpna 1313","1238–1285":"1238–1285","1264–1314":"1264–1314","1251–1313":"1251–1313","about 1261":"okolo 1261","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1314":"1314","1313":"1313","1264":"1264","before 1285":"před 1285","1285":"1285","after 11 August 1313":"po 11. srpna 1313","1251":"1251","about 1251":"okolo 1251","1290":"1290","North Reston, Lincolnshire, England":"North Reston, Lincolnshire, Anglie","Petsoe Manor, Buckinghamshire, England":"Petsoe Manor, Buckinghamshire, Anglie","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1251–after 11 August 1313":"omkring 1251–efter 11. august 1313","1238–1285":"1238–1285","1264–1314":"1264–1314","1251–1313":"1251–1313","about 1261":"omkring 1261","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1314":"1314","1313":"1313","1264":"1264","before 1285":"før 1285","1285":"1285","after 11 August 1313":"efter 11. august 1313","1251":"1251","about 1251":"omkring 1251","1290":"1290","North Reston, Lincolnshire, England":"North Reston, Lincolnshire, England","Petsoe Manor, Buckinghamshire, England":"Petsoe Manor, Buckinghamshire, England","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1251–after 11 August 1313":"circa 1251–na 11 augustus 1313","1238–1285":"1238–1285","1264–1314":"1264–1314","1251–1313":"1251–1313","about 1261":"circa 1261","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1314":"1314","1313":"1313","1264":"1264","before 1285":"vóór 1285","1285":"1285","after 11 August 1313":"na 11 augustus 1313","1251":"1251","about 1251":"circa 1251","1290":"1290","North Reston, Lincolnshire, England":"North Reston, Lincolnshire, England","Petsoe Manor, Buckinghamshire, England":"Petsoe Manor, Buckinghamshire, England","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England"},"en":{"about 1251–after 11 August 1313":"about 1251–after 11 August 1313","1238–1285":"1238–1285","1264–1314":"1264–1314","1251–1313":"1251–1313","about 1261":"about 1261","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1314":"1314","1313":"1313","1264":"1264","before 1285":"before 1285","1285":"1285","after 11 August 1313":"after 11 August 1313","1251":"1251","about 1251":"about 1251","1290":"1290","North Reston, Lincolnshire, England":"North Reston, Lincolnshire, England","Petsoe Manor, Buckinghamshire, England":"Petsoe Manor, Buckinghamshire, England","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Chamberlain","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: status name from Old French <i>chambrelain</i>, Norman French <i>cambrelanc</i>, <i>cambrelen(c)</i> ‘chamberlain’ (of ancient Germanic origin, from <i>kamer</i> ‘chamber, room’, Latin <i>camera</i> (see   Chambers  ) + the diminutive suffix <i>-(l)ing</i>). This was originally the name of an official in charge of the private chambers of his master, but is so widespread in late medieval England that it must sometimes have been used of people of more ordinary status, perhaps as a nickname for an officious or self-important person or for someone who played the role of chamberlain in a folk play, tableau, or ceremony. Compare   Chancellor   for a possible similar usage."],"variants":[{"name":"Chamberlin","meanings":["English: variant of   Chamberlain  .","French: occupational name for an official in charge of the private chambers of his master, from Old French <i>chamberlenc</i> ‘chamberlain’. See also   Chamberlain   and compare above."]},{"name":"Chambers","meanings":["English:","from Middle English <i>chaumbre</i> ‘room (in a house); reception room in a palace or official building’ (Old French <i>chambre</i>). It is identical in implied function with the   Chamberlain  , which denoted an official: to pay <i>in cameram</i> was to pay into the exchequer, of which the <i>camerarius</i> or chamberer was in charge. The surname also applied to clerks employed there. As the office of <i>Chamberlain</i> rose in the social scale, this term remained reserved for more humble servants of the bedchamber or private quarters.","(of Norman origin): habitational name from Les Chambres, Manche (France)."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":8,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":39,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Joan Chamberlain was born about 1251, in North Reston, Lincolnshire, England. She married Sir William Chamberlain Knight about 1261, in North Reston, Lincolnshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died after 11 August 1313, in her hometown."},"et":{"about 1251–after 11 August 1313":"umbes 1251–pärast 11. augustit 1313","1238–1285":"1238–1285","1264–1314":"1264–1314","1251–1313":"1251–1313","about 1261":"umbes 1261","1238":"1238","1259":"125